&lt;h2 id="-what-is-an-operating-system">‚öôÔ∏è What is an Operating System?
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>An operating system (OS) is software that manages computer hardware and software resources, providing common services for programs. It acts as an intermediary between applications and hardware, handling tasks such as:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>üîπ Memory management.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>üîπ Process scheduling.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>üîπ File system management.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>üîπ Device control.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;h3 id="-popular-operating-systems">üåç Popular operating systems:
&lt;/h3>&lt;ul>
&lt;li>üíª &lt;strong>Personal computers&lt;/strong>: Windows, macOS, Linux (Ubuntu, Fedora,&amp;hellip;)&lt;/li>
&lt;li>üì± &lt;strong>Mobile devices&lt;/strong>: iOS, Android&lt;/li>
&lt;li>üñ•Ô∏è &lt;strong>Servers&lt;/strong>: Ubuntu Server, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Windows Server&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>Each operating system has different characteristics, interfaces, and compatibility capabilities. They play crucial roles in system security, performance optimization, and providing consistent user experiences.&lt;/p>
